<paragraph blockId="3.[249,1082,277,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
Nothing is known about the host for this species, nor about its geographic range, since the 
<typeStatus box="[426,517,411,432]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[574,664,411,432]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">paratype</typeStatus>
are the only specimens available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[249,1082,277,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[275,430,437,458]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">Comparisons.</emphasis>
This species does not fit well into any of the subgenera proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cobos" box="[361,512,464,485]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" pagination="23 - 94" refId="ref1433" refString="Cobos, A. 1981. Ensayo sobre los generos de la subfamilia Polycestinae (Coleoptera, Buprestidae) pt. II. Eos, Revista Espanola de Entomologia, Vol. 55 - 56 (1979 - 1980), pp. 23 - 94." type="journal article" year="1981">Cobos (1981)</bibRefCitation>
. In size, color and elytral costate pattern 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nelson" authorityYear="2000" box="[987,1082,464,485]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Polycesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plana">
<emphasis box="[987,1082,464,485]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">P. plana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1858" box="[363,446,491,512]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Polycesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elata">
<emphasis box="[363,446,491,512]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">P. elata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
LeC.; however, in pronotal shape and proportion to elytra, it resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Barr. The" authorityName="Barr. The" box="[383,588,517,539]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Polycesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crypta">
<emphasis box="[383,481,518,539]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">P. crypta</emphasis>
Barr. The
</taxonomicName>
surface configuration of the pronotum is more even than among other North American species, including the recently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Westcott (1998: 21)" authorityName="Westcott" authorityPageNumber="21" authorityYear="1998" box="[337,758,571,592]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Polycesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="constrictinotum">
<emphasis box="[337,537,571,592]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">P. constrictinotum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Westcott" box="[549,758,571,592]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" pagination="18 - 22" refId="ref1480" refString="Westcott, R. L. 1998. Three new species of Buprestidae from Mexico (Coleoptera). Jewel Beetles, No. 6, pp. 18 - 22." type="book chapter" year="1998">Westcott (1998:21)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and the strial punctures are distinctly smaller than in other species, except for 
<taxonomicName authority="Nelson. It" authorityName="Nelson. It" box="[790,1081,597,619]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Polycesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavomaculata">
<emphasis box="[790,968,598,619]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="265">P. flavomaculata</emphasis>
Nelson. It
</taxonomicName>
can be fit into the key to the species presented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Barr" box="[795,953,624,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="265" refId="ref1394" refString="Barr, W. F. 1949. A revision of the species of the genus Polycesta occurring in the United States (Coleoptera, Buprestidae). American Museum Novitates, No. 1432, 42 pp." type="book" year="1949">Barr (1949:11)</bibRefCitation>
as follows:
</paragraph>
